      "text": "Cannondale station opened in March 1852 on the Danbury & Norwalk Railroad, crossing Cannon Road.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannondale%2C_Connecticut"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Actress June Havoc restored Cannon Crossing’s 19th‑century buildings into a boutique village in the late 1970s.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannondale%2C_Connecticut"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Nestled in a picturesque valley along the Norwalk River, Cannondale Village preserves Wilton’s mid‑19th‑century agricultural heritage.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.cannondalevillage.com/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Cannondale stop sits on Metro‑North’s Danbury Line, linking Danbury to South Norwalk.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannondale%2C_Connecticut"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Cannondale’s dark‑brown Wilton Loam soil is praised as the best in Connecticut.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        7
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannondale%2C_Connecticut"
    },
    {
